{"exploration_notes": "The dataset contains 100 confirmed exoplanets discovered between 1992 and 2024, with Transit dominating at 68% of discoveries. There are significant NULL rates in eccentricity (28%) and mass (20%), which may correlate with detection method limitations. Multi-planet systems like 55 Cnc and HR 8799 offer opportunities to study intra-system patterns.

The orbital period spans six orders of magnitude, from sub-day ultra-short-period planets to decades-long directly imaged companions. This enormous dynamic range, combined with method-dependent selection effects, means aggregate statistics are misleading without method-stratified analysis.

Stellar properties cluster around solar-type stars (G/K), with a few notable M-dwarfs and A/F stars. The relationship between stellar type and detected planet properties likely reflects both real physics and observational bias.", "questions": [{"question": "Are the patterns in planet size and orbital period driven by real physical processes or by detection method biases?", "motivation": "Transit and RV methods have fundamentally different sensitivity profiles, so the apparent desert of long-period small planets may be an observational artifact rather than a real feature.", "entry_point": "Compare planet radius and orbital period distributions stratified by discovery method", "difficulty": "moderate"}, {"question": "Do multi-planet systems show evidence of orbital resonances or spacing patterns that single-planet systems lack?", "motivation": "Resonant chains encode formation and migration history. If multi-planet systems cluster near mean-motion resonances, it constrains dynamical models.", "entry_point": "Identify multi-planet systems and compute period ratios between adjacent planets", "difficulty": "deep"}, {"question": "Is there a measurable radius gap in this dataset, and does it shift with stellar type?", "motivation": "The radius gap at ~1.6 Earth radii separates rocky super-Earths from gaseous sub-Neptunes. If its location depends on stellar properties, it constrains atmospheric loss models.", "entry_point": "Histogram planet radii in 0.2 Re bins, then split by stellar spectral type", "difficulty": "simple"}, {"question": "Why do some systems have highly eccentric orbits while others are nearly circular, and can host star properties predict this?", "motivation": "Eccentricity encodes dynamical history — scattering, tidal circularization, or Kozai-Lidov effects. Correlating with stellar mass or multiplicity could reveal the dominant mechanism.", "entry_point": "Plot eccentricity vs semi-major axis, colored by stellar mass, filtering to non-null eccentricities", "difficulty": "moderate"}]}
